          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇺🇬 Uganda:</strong>   
          Kizza Besigye, a Ugandan opposition leader, was <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/prominent-uganda-opposition-figure-kidnapped-and-jailed/a-70828167" target="_blank">reportedly kidnapped</a> in Kenya and returned to Uganda, facing military court charges for unlawful firearm possession, which he denies. His wife, Winnie Byanyima, is questioning the legality of his detention and demanding his release. The incident, occurring during a book launch in Kenya, has drawn criticism of President Museveni’s government for suppressing dissent. Kenya has not commented. This situation highlights ongoing human rights abuses in Uganda, as seen with other opposition figures like Bobi Wine amid rising political repression.</p>
        </mj-text>
